{
  "doc_id": "15312",
  "text": "The identification, cloning, and functional characterization of avian cytokines and their receptors have been hampered by their low sequence homology with their mammalian orthologs, the lack of cross-reactivity of diagnostic tools and of suitable bioassays. Progress was made when the first chicken genome sequence was released [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Since then several cytokine and cytokine receptor families have been identified mainly in chickens [CITATION_3] and to some extend in other avian species [CITATION_4] . The first comprehensive analysis of the chicken TNF/TNFR superfamilies identified numerous members but indicated a reduced complexity in comparison with the mammalian system [CITATION_5] . Several functionally important members of this superfamily seemed to be absent from the avian genome as previously observed for other avian cytokine and chemokine families. Most notably, neither TNF-α nor lymphotoxin-α (LTα) or LTβ in birds were found despite their essential roles in immune defense and lymphoid organ development in mammals [CITATION_6] . Despite significant efforts using conventional database analysis and EST database screening [CITATION_7] as well as expression cloning approaches a chicken TNF-α (chTNF-α) ortholog could not be identified. Furthermore, while the mammalian TNF-α gene is located within the MHC class III region in a cluster with LTα and LTβ, the syntenic region is absent from the chicken MHC locus [CITATION_8] . TNF-α-like biological activities in conditioned media have been reported repeatedly [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] but none of these activities could be further characterized and clearly attributed to a TNF-α-like protein. These observations led some authors to conclude that TNF-α is indeed lacking in birds and arguments were put forward that other TNF family members such as TNF-like ligand 1A might at least partially substitute for its absence [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] as discussed for other missing genes [CITATION_15] .",
